==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧l)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Perh. contr. fr.
<ets>mossul</ets>. See <er>Muslin</er>.]</ety> <def>A thin, soft kind of
muslin.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Icel. <ets>m⟦umac⟧li</ets> a snout,
muzzle, projecting crag; or cf. Ir. & Gael. <ets>meall</ets> a heap of
earth, a mound, a hill or eminence, W. <ets>moel</ets>. Cf.
<er>Mouth</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A promontory; <as>as, the
<ex>Mull</ex> of Cantyre</as>.</def> <mark>[Scot.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A snuffbox made of the small end of a
horn.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. akin to <ets>mold</ets>.
⟦root⟧108. See <er>Mold</er>.]</ety> <def>Dirt; rubbish.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Gower.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>mullen</ets>. See 2d
<er>Muller</er>.]</ety> <def>To powder; to pulverize.</def> <mark>[Prov.
Eng.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To work (over) mentally; to
cogitate; to ruminate; -- usually with <ptcl>over</ptcl>; <as>as, to
<ex>mull</ex> over a thought or a problem</as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.
U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 6 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>An inferior kind of madder prepared
from the smaller roots or the peelings and refuse of the
larger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mull</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 7 ====
HEADWORD: Mull
<hw>Mull</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mulled</conjf> <pr>(m⟦ucr⟧ld)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mulling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From <ets>mulled</ets>, for
<ets>mold</ets>, taken as a p. p.; OE. <ets>mold</ets>-ale funeral ale
or banquet. See <er>Mold</er> soil.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To heat,
sweeten, and enrich with spices; <as>as, to <ex>mull</ex>
wine</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>New cider, <qex>mulled</qex> with ginger warm.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To dispirit or deaden; to dull or blunt.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mullah</ent>⟦br⟧
